# evox2 persistent mutable state
#
# Keep /home outside the slot image so root A/B updates do not replace user data.
# Edit the source and filesystem type if your real layout is different.
#
# Why these specific options:
#
#   This entry is shared across "evox2 hardware (with a real LABEL=HOME
#   partition)" and "QEMU smoke test of the same image" and "live-test
#   USB without a HOME partition". The mount has to do the right thing
#   in all three cases:
#
#     a) HOME partition exists  -> mount it on /home, users get persistent
#                                  data across A/B switches.
#     b) HOME partition absent  -> /home falls back to the empty directory
#                                  baked into the rootfs. useradd
#                                  --create-home, shell login, and
#                                  cd /home/$user all just work.
#
#   - nofail                       Do not block local-fs.target on this
#                                  mount. With nofail, systemd treats
#                                  the mount as "wanted, not required",
#                                  removes the ordering edge to
#                                  local-fs.target, and a missing device
#                                  is not a boot failure.
#
#   - x-systemd.device-timeout=2s  Default device-timeout is 90s. On
#                                  hosts without a HOME partition that
#                                  is 90s of `Timed out waiting for
#                                  device dev-disk-by\x2dlabel-HOME.device`
#                                  before nofail kicks in. 2s is enough
#                                  for the kernel to enumerate the disks.
#
#   We deliberately do NOT use x-systemd.automount here. autofs returns
#   "No such device" to userspace whenever the underlying mount fails,
#   which breaks `cd /home/$user` and shell login on any boot where
#   the HOME partition is absent (QEMU, fresh USBs). Without automount,
#   a failed nofail mount leaves /home as an ordinary directory in the
#   rootfs, which is exactly what we want.
#
# Examples for other filesystem types / sources:
#   UUID=<uuid>          /home  ext4   nofail,x-systemd.device-timeout=2s  0  2
#   PARTUUID=<partuuid>  /home  ext4   nofail,x-systemd.device-timeout=2s  0  2
#   LABEL=HOME           /home  btrfs  subvol=@home,compress=zstd,nofail,x-systemd.device-timeout=2s  0  0
LABEL=HOME /home ext4 nofail,x-systemd.device-timeout=2s 0 2
